  "doc_id": "7271",
  "text": "These studies provide the first insights into how insulin influences NAc excitatory transmission. Insulin's effects and the underlying mechanism in the NAc differ dramatically from those found in other brain regions and at earlier stages in neural development. This highlights the potential complexity of predicting insulin's actions on overall neural function in both obese and lean states. The involvement of opioid receptor activation in the response to insulin found here is consistent with the ability of opioids in the NAc to enhance food intake and hedonic responses to palatable foods [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] , and with conditioned increases in insulin in anticipation of palatable food consumption [CITATION_4] . Thus, brain insulin receptors may be a viable target for modulating food motivation, and possibly motivation for non-physiological reinforces like cocaine [CITATION_5] . Finally, the NAc receives inhibitory input from GABAergic neurons in the VTA [CITATION_6] , in addition to local collateralization of MSNs and aspiny GABAergic interneurons [CITATION_7] [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] . Thus, it will be important for future studies to determine whether disinhibition produced by insulin is selective to different sources of GABA within the NAc.",
